          "CAPA effectiveness verification plan: (1) IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS VERIFICATION — (a) System access controls: conduct penetration testing — have IT attempt to delete data, access admin functions, and perform unauthorized operations using analyst-level credentials. Success criteria: 100% of unauthorized attempts blocked by the system. Timeline: within 2 weeks of implementation, (b) Second-person data review: audit 100 consecutive analytical reports post-implementation. Success criteria: 100% show documented Level 1, Level 2, and Level 3 review with electronic signatures. Timeline: 30-day monitoring period, (c) After-hours controls: attempt after-hours instrument access without pre-approval. Verify alert generation to supervisors and QA. Success criteria: 100% of unauthorized attempts detected and escalated. (2) PROCESS CORRECTIVE ACTIONS VERIFICATION — (a) Single-injection compliance: audit 200 consecutive HPLC runs. Success criteria: zero undocumented re-injections. Any re-injection has documented justification and supervisor pre-approval, (b) OOS investigation turnaround: track all OOS investigations for 6 months post-SOP revision. Success criteria: ≥90% completed within 5 business days, (c) Audit trail review compliance: verify daily review completion rate. Success criteria: ≥98% of scheduled daily reviews completed with documented findings. (3) DOCUMENTATION & GOVERNANCE VERIFICATION — (a) DIO effectiveness: verify the DIO has conducted independent data integrity assessments per the defined schedule. Success criteria: 100% of scheduled assessments completed with findings reported to Site Head, (b) Part 11 SOP harmonization: QA audit of all 23 revised SOPs for Part 11 compliance using the standardized checklist. Success criteria: zero critical gaps identified, (c) Self-inspection: conduct a full data integrity self-inspection per the updated SOP. Success criteria: findings limited to minor observations, no systemic gaps. (4) TECHNOLOGY VERIFICATION — (a) CDS upgrade validation: completed IQ/OQ/PQ with zero critical deviations. All configured controls (access, audit trail, signatures) verified functional, (b) LIMS implementation: validated per GAMP 5 with Part 11 compliance confirmed. Automated data capture verified against manual calculations (±0.1% agreement), (c) Anomaly detection: retrospectively run the detection algorithms against the historical falsified data set. Success criteria: system detects ≥95% of the known falsification instances. (5) TRAINING & CULTURE VERIFICATION — (a) Competency assessment: all GMP personnel complete scenario-based data integrity assessment. Success criteria: ≥90% pass rate with documented remediation for failures, (b) Anonymous reporting: verify the hotline/portal is operational. Conduct a test submission. Track reporting volume over 6 months — an increase is expected and healthy, (c) Workload assessment: verify analyst-to-sample ratios are within 15-20 samples per analyst per shift for 3 consecutive months, (d) Culture survey: conduct baseline survey within 1 month and follow-up at 6 and 12 months. Success criteria: statistically significant improvement in data integrity culture scores. (6) CAPA CLOSURE CRITERIA — ALL of the following must be satisfied: (a) All 47 action items verified as implemented AND effective by independent verifiers, (b) Zero data integrity findings in the next internal self-inspection (conducted ≥6 months after CAPA implementation), (c) Zero recurrence of unauthorized data deletion, re-injection without justification, or after-hours unauthorized access for 12 consecutive months, (d) FDA inspection completed with no data-integrity-related Warning Letter observations (if applicable), (e) Independent retesting of all 87 affected batch retained samples completed with disposition decisions documented, (f) All product recalls completed with confirmed market withdrawal, (g) Management Review Board sign-off on closure, (h) Post-closure monitoring plan: continue enhanced oversight for an additional 12 months after formal CAPA closure, with defined triggers for CAPA reopening if any effectiveness metric deteriorates. (7) FDA INSPECTION READINESS — Present to the FDA a complete CAPA package: investigation report with forensic evidence, root cause analysis, contributing factor analysis, 47 CAPA actions with implementation status and effectiveness verification plan, timeline (Gantt chart), and trend data. Demonstrate that the company discovered the problem itself, investigated thoroughly, took decisive patient safety action, and is implementing genuine systemic reform. Transparency and thoroughness are the strategy.",
